Now featuring special guest DataKind DC!

6:30 - 7:00 Participants arrive and socialize. 

7:00 - 7:15 Group introductions and announcements from participants and organizers.

7:15 - 9:00 Hacking! Project teams break out to work.  If you are new, join the new member orientation.

~7:30 Food delivered.

9:15 We head out to happy hour.

Notes: 

• The building is wheelchair-accessible with advance notice. Please contact us to let us know.

• Text 202-791-4101 for entry if no one is at the door.

• Bring cash for food and drink! Pay what you can.

If you are new to Code for DC: 

• Bring a laptop if you can (it’s ok if you can’t).

• Take a look at our projects.

• Review the Code for DC Code of Conduct.

• Feel free to contact us with any questions, concerns, etc.

• If you had a good time, join Google Group, Slack, and Meetup to stay in the loop.

other.description:
This month we are joining several Maptime chapters around the world who are participating in Missing Maps mapathons. 

Missing Maps is a humanitarian mapping project with the objective to map the most vulnerable places in the developing world, in order that international and local NGOs and individuals can use the maps and data to better respond to crises affecting the areas. We will be mapping areas where the data is literally missing from OpenStreetMap. 

Mapping beginners are welcome! If you are new to OSM please sign up for an account beforehand, and if you have some time before the mapathon, there are training videos to provide some background. At the start of the mapathon we will be going through a short tutorial on OpenStreetMap and the Tasking Manager to get everyone up to speed. 

Please bring a laptop. If you have one, external mouses are handy for easier mapping. Pizza will be provided for all mappers (thanks to Missing Maps!). 

Name badges are required for this mapathon, so please RSVP through Meetup. See you there!
other.how_to_find_us: There will be someone in the lobby waiting to escort groups up to the Disaster Operations Center. If not, call 202 594 4892.

other.description:
Most Ruby on Rails apps require user registration and authentication mechanisms. Authentication determines if users are who they say they are, usually through a username/password combo. As anyone who’s completed the Hartl tutorial knows, developing these mechanisms from scratch requires a lot of time and effort. 

But thankfully--especially when you're new to Rails--there are Ruby gems like Devise that can handle that code-writing for us.

In this meetup, we’ll discuss the basics of authentication and then walk you through a short tutorial:

Step 1: We’ll create a new app in Rails

Step 2: Using the Devise gem, we’ll set up a full-fledged user authentication system within minutes.

Step 3: We’ll discuss how to customize Devise.

Step 4: We’ll discuss how you can make your users even happier by allowing them to access your app without registering for a new account and simply log in using their existing Amazon, Facebook, Twitter, and other social media accounts. 

Bring your laptop to follow along. Any extra time will be used for questions, guided walkthroughs, or personal projects you want to work on. 

We look forward to seeing you there!

Meetup Agenda 

• 6:30pm - Quick introductions

• 6:45pm - Authentication in Rails

• 8:15 - 8:30pm - Wrap Up

Looking for something to work on?

For those who are new to coding or new to Rails, we recommend Michael Hartl's Rails Tutorial. For those who have some experience already but are looking for projects, we recommend Mackenzie Child's 12 in 12 apps. You are always welcome to come and work on something else if you like.

Contact policy at buildings that need access

Certain building managements requires meetup hosts to let people in and do not encourage them being contacted. Please respect the policy, in case the location requires access to the building contact the group lead if information is provided, or drop a comment on the meetup page. We'll come and get you. 

Want to be a Ruby on Rails Study Group leader?

If you are passionate about learning ROR with fellow awesome women and want to help us, come on out! Drop us a message or email us and let us know that you are interested in helping us with the Rails study group!

RESOURCES

These are the resources that members have been following along, feel free to suggest if you have more to add!

</a><a href="https://github.com/womenwhocodedc/organization/blob/master/learning-resources/ruby-on-rails/rails_guide.md">https://github.com/womenwhocodedc/organization/blob/master/learning-resources/ruby-on-rails/rails_guide.md

Location: Google Reston, 1875 Explorer St. Suite 1000. Reston, VA 20190

Agenda: 

6:00 - 6:30 PM Networking and Pizza!

6:30 - 7:30 Kubernetes Talk and Demo - David Aronchick -  Lead Product Manager for Kubernetes project

7:00 - 8:00 Post Event Networking 

Please make sure to Fill the First and Last Name to gain access to the building

Abstract:

Want to run containers at scale in the same way that Google does? In 2014, Google released Kubernetes, the open source container orchestration tool built on the same concepts they use to manage the largest public infrastructure deployment in the world - their own. 

Almost two years later, Kubernetes is a mature, sophisticated and, dare we say, easy to use orchestration solution. Come hear David Aronchick, lead product manager for Kubernetes project, and a core engineer on Kubernetes team, talk about the present (and future) of Kubernetes, and how to use it to solve development and business blockers.

Speaker: David Aronchick -  Lead Product Manager for Kubernetes project

@aronchick 


Please make sure to Fill the First and Last Name to gain access to the building.

Sponsors: Google Cloud Platform

WWC DC would like to introduce Charlyn Keating, an entrepreneur and app developer who has led technology projects for high-profile clients including Disney, Wal-Mart, Mobil Oil, Cirque du Soleil, and Hotel Monaco.


About Charlyn:
-Charlyn is a published author, speaker, and television and video host, she organized and hosted last year's hugely successful Appreneur Summit, an international online conference for independent app and game developers.

-Charlyn is a theme park aficionado who's currently hard at work building an extensive and magical app portfolio for Disney World vacationers.


Event Details


Members will get a chance to ask her anything related to:
-App Development
-Marketing & Social Media
-Mobile Programming

How do I sign up?
-Request to join our Slack channel: http://bit.ly/wwcdcslack
-Join the #ama channel
-Tweet using #AppreneurAMA

Schedule
-Tuesday May 24 @ 12:00PM EST: We will kick off the event and you can start asking your questions
-Wednesday May 25 @ 12:00PM EST: We will remind members to ask their final questions by 9:00PM
-Thursday May 26 @ 5:00PM EST: End of the AMA

During this period Charlyn will answer your questions. Members are welcome to post questions at any point during the AMA from noon Tuesday to 9:00pm EST Wednesday.

This event is for everyone, and may be really helpful for aspiring entrepreneurs, developers, those interested in building an app and those interested in the app development process. Come join us on slack.

other.description:
Women in Data Science II - Nearly two years ago, we held an event featuring 3 fantastic and female speakers, all data science leaders in academia, industry, and startups with the goal of hosting a technical meetup with more than 50% female attendance. Based on the resounding success of this first event, we had to host a second one but, this time, we are doing so with the new meetup group, Women Data Scientists DC!

More speakers will be announced as we get closer to the event.

SCHEDULE

Please note that we will be using the same schedule as before to facilitate community interaction.

6:00 PM - Doors open

6:10 PM - Introductions

6:15 PM - First Speaker

6:45 PM - Intermission and Food

7:00 PM - Second Speaker

7:30 PM - Short Break

7:35 PM - Panel Discussion


SPEAKERS


Amy O’Connor leads Cloudera's team of vertical industry experts, business value consultants and principal architects, and is the US Telecommunications SME. She advises customers globally as they introduce Big Data solutions and adopt enterprise-wide Big Data delivery capabilities. Amy was recently named by Information Management as one of the “10 Big Data Experts to Know” and "12 Inspiring Women In Data Science, Big Data" by Information Week. Prior to joining Cloudera, Amy built and ran Nokia’s Big Data team, developing and managing Nokia’s data asset and leading a team of data scientists to drive insights. Previously Amy was vice president of services marketing and also led strategy for the software and storage business units of Sun Microsystems. Amy has an extensive background in the Hadoop ecosystem, in building big data skills and teams, and in developing business-focused analytical use cases.  She holds her M.B.A. from Northeastern University and her bachelor degrees in computer science and electrical engineering from the University of Connecticut.

Dr. Marie desJardins is the Associate Dean for Academic Affairs in the College of Engineering and Information Technology (COEIT) at the University of Maryland, Baltimore County (UMBC).  She is also a Professor in UMBC’s Department of Computer Science and Electrical Engineering, where she has been a member of the faculty since 2001.  She was a[masked] American Council of Education Fellow, the[masked] UMBC Presidential Teaching Professor, and an inaugural Hrabowski Academic Innovation Fellow.  Her research is in artificial intelligence, focusing on the areas of machine learning, multi-agent systems, planning, iand nteractive AI techniques.  Current research projects include learning in the context of planning and decision making, analyzing and visualizing uncertainty in machine learning, trust modeling in multiagent systems, and intelligent tutoring systems for learning to program.

She is also highly visible in the state-level and national computing education community, focusing on K-12 computing curricula, diversity and inclusion in computing, innovative pedagogical methods.  She currently leads the NSF-funded “CS Matters in Maryland” project to develop curriculum and teacher training for the new AP CS Principles course, serves as lead PI for the Maryland team on the Expanding Computing Education Alliance, chairs the Maryland Computing Education Steering Committee, and serves as the university liaison for the Maryland chapter of the Computer Science Teachers Association.

Dr. desJardins received her Ph.D. in 1992 from the University of California, Berkeley.  Her dissertation research focused on developing techniques to allow autonomous agents to learn useful models of their environments without being supervised by a human designer.  From[masked], she was a member of the research staff at SRI International in Menlo Park, California.  Her research there focused primarily on autonomous and mixed-initiative methods for planning, learning, and multi-agent systems.

Dr. desJardins has published over 120 scientific papers in journals, conferences, and workshops.  She is an Associate Editor of the Journal of Artificial Intelligence Research, is a member of the editorial board of AI Magazine, and was the Program Cochair for AAAI-13.  She has previously served as AAAI Liaison to the Board of Directors of the Computing Research Association, Vice-Chair of ACM's SIGART, and AAAI Councillor. She is an ACM Distinguished Member, a AAAI Senior Member, a member and former chair of UMBC's Honors College Advisory Board, the former chair of UMBC's Faculty Affairs Committee, and a member of the advisory board for UMBC's Center for Women in Technology.

Dr. desJardins is active in teaching, mentoring, and advising students.  She received the 2014 NCWIT Undergraduate Research Mentoring Award and the 2016 CRA Undergraduate Research Faculty Mentoring Award.  She was named one of UMBC's ten "Professors Not to Miss" in 2011, and is regularly sought out to give invited talks to student groups.  She has been involved with the AAAI/SIGART Doctoral Consortium as chair, co-chair, mentor, and/or reviewer annually since 2000.  She has advised three postdoctoral researchers, 13 Ph.D. students (11 to completion), 27 M.S. students (24 to completion), over 70 undergraduate researchers, and four high school student interns.

Data Visualization DC and Graphicacy Present:


The Major League Data Viz Challenge Awards!

Join your fellow data visualizers on Wednesday May, 25th for the Data Viz Challenge Awards. This May DVDC and our partners at Graphicacy will be awarding prizes for the best data visualizations of 2016!

Data Viz entries we received in March and have been judged on Form, Function, Originality, and Effectiveness. We are honored to be giving out the following prizes to the winners:

• Grand prize: $1,000 

• Gold: $500

• Silver: $300

• Bronze: $150

The judges include Sean Gonzalez, Nathaniel Pearlman, Richard Saul Wurman, Taegan Goddard, Nicco Mele, Patrick Ruffini, and Nicole Melander:

The Major League Data Viz Challenge Awards will be held at Capital One’s McLean, Virginia office (1680 Capital One Drive, McLean, VA[masked]), right across the street from the Silver Line’s McLean Metro Station, and we recommend that you take the train if you want to stay for data drinks after. 

To access Capital One’s Mclean Headquarters, please confirm your RSVP as soon as possible, and bring a recent government ID with you the night of the event.

We look forward to seeing you!  

Agenda:

• 6:30 - Food/Drink, Networking

• 7:00 - Introductions, Announcements

• 7:10 - Presentation #1

• 7:35 - Presentation #2

• 8:00 - Q&A, Break

• 8:10 - Winner Presentation

• 8:35 - Awards

• 8:40 - Q&A

Announcing DATABLE!

Are you Datable? Apply here.

Datable is speed dating for Data Practitioners and Data Driven Companies.

Datable is a new way for DC2 to provide career services to our community. Our educational events are free and open but attending them all can become a full time job! So DC2 is gathering our career minded members and the best data driven companies and bringing the best together at Datable.

Hack && Tell will be at WeWork Chinatown this month! Everyone is looking forward to hearing about *your* cool hack. Presentation signups are here:

http://bit.ly/presentatdc

The format is informal, engaging, and friendly: presenters have *5* minutes to show off their hack (it goes faster than you’d expect) and then the audience has 5 minutes to ask questions, make jokes, and suggest ideas and feedback. The hacks that people present are anything from how to train your dog to text you when it needs a walk to [something more serious... like blenders made out of artichokes]. Show us what you’ve got! But remember: no startup pitches, no dull work projects, no deckware!

If you’re interested in presenting, complete this short form to let us know: http://bit.ly/presentatdc

See you at the meetup! We try to start on-time at 6:30. Sometimes we have free food (bonus!). Big thanks to WeWork for hosting us! We love WeWork! We love you! We love hacks! <3

other.description:
Interested in learning how to build Android apps with an awesome group of women? Looking to build your first app or build on existing skills? Come to our weekly Android Lab! We welcome women with all levels of Android experience (including none). ***Please bring your laptop to this event as computers will not be provided.***


Resources

Beginners should check out our Android Getting Started Guide. It's chock full of information to get you up and running. It is a work in progress and we'll be adding as we go. Suggestions welcomed!

All Women Welcome

This event is intended to be exclusively open for women; we are trans* friendly.

Can't Come This Week, but Want to Stay in Touch?

Please join our Slack group to talk about all things Android.
other.name: Android Lab

other.description:
We're a group of women who want to learn and develop our Python scripting skills. Some of us are professional developers and data scientists, others are hobbyists, and some are just beginning. The study group is intended for everyone who wishes to learn more about the Python programming language. Folks of all skill levels are welcome!


We host beginners night on the first Wednesday of every month, which caters especially for absolute beginners and people with basic familiarity.

All other study group nights will generally cover more advanced topics and work on projects more in depth, according to everyone's interests.

(Please bring a laptop!) 

Note: This Women Who Code DC event is intended to be exclusively open for women; we are trans* friendly.
other.name: Python Lab

other.description:
Data, privacy, and application design


When dealing with research data, you have to be careful to protect user privacy. This can make it difficult to get hold of good data for testing. Truth Initiative has written a system for migrating sensitive data that protects user privacy while preserving useful properties for testing. We'll walk through the design of the system and how we met some of the challenges in building it.


Our Speaker


Matt Bowen is a senior software engineer at Truth Initiative, where he writes software to study better ways to help people quit smoking. He's also the vice president of DC Python's board.
other.name: Protecting User Privacy with Fuzzy-feeling Test Data

other.description:
Front End Hack Night (FEHN) is a study group where women can come together and help each other learn and understand web development. We welcome devs of all levels and encourage those with more experience to help out those that are just starting. There's always at least one mentor or leader present to help you with best practices or to guide you through if you are stuck with a nasty problem! Laptops

In order to maximize your benefits from FEHN, please bring your laptop. Extra computers will not be available at the event. Even if you have never coded before, you will be coding at FEHN!

Meetup Agenda Every study group will have the following format:
• 6:30pm - Setup

• 6:40 - 6:50pm - Quick introductions

• 6:50 - 8:15pm - Code!

• 8:15 - 8:30pm - Wrap Up

To learn more about us please visit our Github page - http://bit.ly/frontendhacknight
